## Can any tool handle podcast and TV attribution?

Rockerbox's strength is measuring hard-to-track channels. But be realistic about limitations:

<div class="my-6 not-prose grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
  <div class="bg-emerald-50 rounded-lg p-5 border border-emerald-200">
    <h4 class="font-semibold text-emerald-800 mb-3">What We Can Track</h4>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-emerald-900">
      <li>Vanity URL visits (~10-30% of actual impact)</li>
      <li>Promo code redemptions (~5-15% of actual impact)</li>
      <li>Survey responses ("How did you hear about us?")</li>
      <li>MMM correlation (aggregate, not individual)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div class="bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-5 border border-amber-200">
    <h4 class="font-semibold text-amber-800 mb-3">What We Can't Track</h4>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-amber-900">
      <li>Direct website visits from podcast listeners</li>
      <li>Word of mouth triggered by podcasts</li>
      <li>Brand recall without immediate action</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="my-4 p-4 bg-slate-100 rounded-lg border border-slate-200 text-sm text-slate-700">
  <strong>Reality:</strong> All podcast attribution is estimation. Rockerbox is the best at estimation, but it's still estimation.
</div>

**Incrementality tests can validate podcast impact** more definitively—turn off podcasts in test markets, measure revenue difference.

